        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Static Class Design</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A static class is defined as a class that contains only static members (of course besides the instance members inherited from <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Object?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> and possibly a private constructor).</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Some languages provide built-in support for static classes.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In C# 2.0 and later, when a class is declared to be static, it is sealed, abstract, and no instance members can be overridden or declared.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Static classes are a compromise between pure object-oriented design and simplicity.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>They are commonly used to provide shortcuts to other operations (such as <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.IO.File?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph>), holders of extension methods, or functionality for which a full object-oriented wrapper is unwarranted (such as <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Environment?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph>).</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">**</bpt>✓ DO<ept id="p1">**</ept> use static classes sparingly.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Static classes should be used only as supporting classes for the object-oriented core of the framework.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">**</bpt>X DO NOT<ept id="p1">**</ept> treat static classes as a miscellaneous bucket.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">**</bpt>X DO NOT<ept id="p1">**</ept> declare or override instance members in static classes.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><bpt id="p1">**</bpt>✓ DO<ept id="p1">**</ept> declare static classes as sealed, abstract, and add a private instance constructor if your programming language does not have built-in support for static classes.</source>
        </trans-unit>
